            <div type="edition" subtype="diplomatic" ana="b1">
                <p><g ref="cross">+</g>ΚΕΒΟΗΘΙΤΩΝΔΟΥΛΩΖΟΥ <lb/> 
                    ΛΕΩΝΟΣΚΑΛΛΙΝΙΚΟΥΖΑΔΑΚΑ <lb/> 
                    ΘΩΝΚΤΟΥΣΦΙΛΟΥΣΑΥΤΟΥΑΜΗΝ <lb/> 
                    ΚΕ<g ref="cross">+</g> </p>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transcription" ana="b1">
                <p><g ref="cross">+</g>
                    <expan><abbr>Κ</abbr><ex>ύρι</ex><abbr>ε</abbr></expan> Βωηθι τῶν δοῦλῳ σου
                    <lb/> Λέωνος Καλλινίκου Ζαδακάθων <expan><abbr>κ</abbr><ex>αί</ex></expan> τούς
                    φίλους αὐτοῦ. Ἀμήν. <lb/>
                    <expan><abbr>Κ</abbr><ex>ύρι</ex><abbr>ε</abbr></expan>
                    <g ref="cross">+</g>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p>Lord help your servant Leon son of Kallinikos of Zadacatha and his companions. Anen. O Lord . </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1">
                <p> Published. The names of this inscription occur regularly and are frequent in the
                    papyri and inscriptions from Egypt. Ζαδακάθα is most probably the place in
                    southern Transjordan, identified with Ain-es-Sadaka. Its earliest mention is
                    probably that of Ptolemy, who mentions a place by the name of Ζαναάθα in Arabia
                    Petraea. In the Notitia Dignitatum the place is mentioned by the name of
                    Zodocatha, and it is told that the Equités promoti indigenae were stationed
                    there. In the Peutinger map, it is identified by the name of Zadagatta, at a
                    distance of 8 miles from Hawara. In the form in which it figures in our
                    inscription it also appears in the Tax-edict of Beersheba.</p>
            </div>
